The Data

IMPORTANT!!!! An in-depth video explaining the data can be found HERE. Please watch this short >10min video before getting started.

Briefly, you have been given a zipped directory âRaw Data.zipâ which contains two kinds of files: .mats and .csvs. The .csvs are from three experiments, one where the group size was one (GS1), one where the group size was five (GS5) and one where the group size was 10 (GS10). We are only interested in the GS10 .csv files.

Each GS10 csv file corresponds to a single trial and contains the following:

  • X and Y coordinates for each animal, where each row is a frame, and each animalâs tracks are stacked in long-format.
  • Animal which tells you which animal was being tracked. There are 10 animals per trial.
  • Trial which is the trial number. This should be the same as the trial number in the file name.
  • Date which is the day the trial was conducted
  • Weather which is the weather at the beginning of the trial, stored as âCloudyâ or âSunnyâ
  • Temp which is the temperature at the beginning of the trial in Fahrenheit
  • TOD which is the time of day when the trial began (all trials were conducted in the morning)

Your task will be to select only the GS10 csv files from the directory, combine the raw track data and metadata from each trial into two files with all the trials combined in UNIX, and then wrangle/plot them in R (plus some other fun stuff along the way).

Notably, if you run into hiccups along the way and are unable to generate the files in the UNIX section, we have included them as well (TrackData.csv and MetaData.csv) so that you can see what they should look like, and can use them to finish the R section if needed.

Are you ready?

Problem 04: How does Weather, Temperature, Time-of-Day, and Smoke impact the animals movement?

We want to know how the Weather, Temperature, Time of day, and Smoke from the forest fire impacted the animalâs movements. Specifically, we want to know whether it changed the VELOCITY at which the animalsâ moved, or how WIGGLY the path was that they took.

We can calculate their VELOCITY as: the distance between where they started the trial and where they ended the trial divided by the time it took them to complete the trial (weâll convert this to be in units of inches per second)

We can calculate how WIGGLY their path was by calculating something called the âstraightness indexâ which is: the distance between the beginning and end of their path (i.e.Â the distance they would have traveled if they moved in a perfectly straight line) divided by the distance they actually traveled (i.e.Â the sum of the distance between each step). This gives us a number bound between 0 and 1, where 1 is a perfectly straight line and 0 is Brownian motion (very wiggly).

Once we have both of these metrics calculated for every animal, we will then calculate the AVERAGE velocity and straightness index for each trial, and merge it with the metadata.

Letâs get started!

Step A: Wrangling the data frameâCalculating the time and distances for each individual

Your first task is to calculate the following variables for each individual:

  • The Time it took each animal to complete their track (in frames)

  • The Straight Line Distance the animal moved (the distance between the beginning and end of their track)

  • The Actual Distance the animal moved (the sum of the distance the animal moved each step)

To do this we will need to use three new functions we might not have seen before: lag(), first() / last(), and n()

  • lag() gives you the value of the row that came BEFORE/ABOVE the current row. So if, for example, we wanted to make a new column that contained the value of each row minus the value of the row before it, we could do mutate(NewColumn=OriginalColumn-lag(OriginalColumn). This will give us an NA for the first row (since thereâs nothing before it) and otherwise would give us the value of each row minus the value of the preceding row. (Note: the function lead() does the same but in reverse, it gives the value of the row after/below of the current row). This is a vectorized function, like our vectorized if_else() statement, so it runs iteratively over each row, meaning we donât need to use a for loop â yay!

  • first()/last() gives you the value from the first/last row. This is particular useful when using a group_by, as it will give you the first and last value of the GROUPED data (i.e.Â the first/last value for each individual group, not just the first/last value of the whole dataframe)

  • n() when used within a summarise will give you the total number of rows contained within each group.

IMPORTANT: Remember, the formula to calculate the distance between two points is distance=sqrt( (X1-X2)^2 + (Y1-Y2)^2)

We want to produce the following dataframe. Hints are below.

Hint 6: Calculating the straight-line distanceâbig hint

In a summarise, use Diff_StrtLine_X = ( first(X) - last(X) )^2 and Diff_StrtLine_Y = ( first(Y) - last(Y) )^2 then you can do Dist_StrtLine = sqrt( Diff_StrtLine_X + Diff_StrtLine_Y) )
